                <change who="#admin" when="2021-11-02T14:13:45.147Z" type="attribution" xml:id="UT23703-096-020-10" source="tengyur-data-3824-3980_PH_new_v2.4.xml">
                    <desc>The attribution of this text (Toh. 3843) to Nāgārjuna appears to be in error as it is very clearly a Cittamātra text and is identical in content (though
            a different translation) to Toh. 4058 attributed to Vasubandhu.</desc>
                </change>
                <change who="#admin" when="2021-11-02T14:13:45.147Z" type="title" xml:id="UT23703-096-020-11" source="tengyur-data-3824-3980_PH_new_v2.4.xml">
                    <desc>The Sanskrit title provided (Toh. 3843) is a back-translation from the Tibetan, which itself is only marginally intelligible, hence the title provided is taken
            from a translation of the extant Sanskrit manuscript.</desc>
                </change>
                <change who="#admin" when="2021-11-02T14:13:45.147Z" type="general" xml:id="UT23703-096-020-12" source="tengyur-data-3824-3980_PH_new_v2.4.xml">
                    <desc>The text presents a straight forward exposition with illustrations of the “Three Natures” (trisvabhāva) theory common to the Cittamātra school. Although
            there is a Madhyamaka interpretation of the “Three Natures” (as presented in the “Maitreya” chapters of the Eighteen Thousand Line Perfection of Wisdom Sūtra [chapter 83], and the
            Twenty-Five Thousand Line Perfection of Wisdom Sūtra [chapter 72]), that interpretation is not what is found here.</desc>
                </change>
